properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls develop late this afternoon and possibly persist through Saturday. Locally heavy snow squalls are expected to develop late this afternoon as strong southwesterly to westerly winds develop off of Georgian Bay. These snow squalls could possibly last until Saturday evening. Local snowfall amounts of 15 to 30 cm are possible with these snow squalls. However, if the strongest snow squall from Georgian Bay is able to lock in and become stationary for a few hours, snowfall amounts exceeding 40 cm are possible. Given the strong winds gusting up to 70 km/h, areas of near zero visibilities in blowing snow and heavy falling snow could make travel hazardous across the region. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow and wind is expected Monday. Locations: southern, central, and eastern Newfoundland. Time span: Monday morning through Monday night. Remarks: A low pressure system tracking southeast of Newfoundland is forecast to bring significant amounts of snow to parts of the province. Snow is expected to begin Monday morning for southern portions of the island, and will spread north over central and eastern regions in the following hours. There is potential for the snow to mix with or change over to rain over southern portions of the Avalon Monday afternoon. At this time it is too early to provide specific accumulations. Visibility will be reduced in snow and blowing snow most of the day. Conditions will improve by early Tuesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. A ridge of arctic high pressure keeping skies relatively clear has allowed for a very cold air mass to move into portions of northern Manitoba from Nunavut. Along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h, extreme cold wind chills of -45 or colder are expected over the next few days as the stagnant area of high pressure remains parked over the province. Extreme cold warnings will likely be expanded to include most of the province come Friday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls this evening into tonight. Locally heavy snow squalls are forecast to develop late this afternoon. These snow squalls are then expected to continue into tonight and possibly last until Saturday morning. Local snowfall amounts near 15 cm are expected. However, if the strongest snow squall from Lake Erie is able to lock in and become stationary for a few hours, snowfall amounts of up to 25 cm are possible. Given the strong southwesterly winds gusting up to 80 km/h, areas of near zero visibility in blowing snow and heavy snow will be a concern. Motorists should consider changing travel plans accordingly. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls are likely to move in late this afternoon and continue through Saturday morning. Local snowfall accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are expected in these snow squalls. The combination of strong and gusty winds reaching up to 60 km/h and heavy snow at times will result in a significant reduction in visibility in local blowing snow. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
